You're right, if you have a FEN notation of a chess board position, you can create a LaTeX code that will display the position on the screen. To do this, you will need to define the FEN notation in the LaTeX code and use the \chessboard command to display it on the screen. Here's an example of how you can do this:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}

\begin{document}
\begin{chessboard}[fen="8/8/8/8/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"] % Define the FEN notation here
  e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. h3 Bb7 10. d4 Re8 11. Bd2 Bf8 12. a3 c5 13. dxc5 Qxd1+ 14. Rxd1 Ne5 15. Nxe5 dxe5
\end{chessboard}
\end{document}
```

Here, we define the FEN notation as "8/8/8/8/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1", which means it's an empty chess board with white pieces and no pawns, with white to move and starting from move number zero (the first move is move one). We then use the \chessboard command to display the board on the screen with black squares on the top and bottom rows and white squares in the middle six rows, with all pieces in their standard positions, including the king on e8, queen on d1, rook on e1, bishop on b7, knight on d6, pawns on a2-h7, and all other pieces in their default starting positions. Note that there are several packages available for LaTeX that provide additional functionality for displaying chess boards, such as \usepackage{chessboard}, but this example should get you started if you don't have access to one of those packages or if you want to create a simple chess board using basic LaTeX commands.

